Connect each quadrant to either 'power'
or 'sink' (never both) by cutting the
existing track or soldering a 'blob'
to bridge the connectors. A full circle
indicates the the jumper is shorted by
default.
Place an SMD between the quadrants. By default the left
quadtants are 'power' (the LED's anode) and the right
quadrants are 'sink' (the cathode). It is possible to
configure the circuit to test a four-pin common anode
LED using the jumpers.
J1 allows input of power when the USB isn't plugged in.
Id the connection of the jumper above it is cut, then
an enable signal needs to be connected. This allows
a PWM input to control the LED.
Connect the USB plug on the
top side of the board
Test LEDs with legs using these
connections. The square pad is the
for the anode.
The circuit uses two NPN bipolar transistors and two
resistors in order to drive the LED with constant current
regardless of input power. This isn't a perfect driver, but
for most applications it performs very well, and it quite
simple.
It relies on the near constant drop between the base and emitter of
T2 to set the voltage actoss R1.
Some questions:
* What is the voltage across R1 (point A)?
* What is the current going through R1? What is the current
through the tested LED? Are the values the same? If not, why not?
* Why did we supply a 33Ω resistor and not a 'better' value?
* What values of reistors for R1, R2, and R3 would you use
to get 5.7mA, 12mA, and 2.5mA?
